My intuition is that proving #P-hardness for linear optimization over $ C_{p^{n+2}} $—a polytope encoding marginal contributions in cooperative games—can be approached not just as a standalone complexity result, but as a gateway to understanding the intrinsic difficulty of verifying semivalues (e.g., Shapley values, Banzhaf index) for LTFs, which are fundamental in interpretable ML. While prior work has studied the hardness of computing exact Shapley values, less attention has been paid to *verification*—i.e., deciding whether a given value assignment is a valid semivalue—which may have different complexity characteristics. Moreover, LTFs induce symmetry and sparsity in their influence structure, suggesting that reductions from known #P-complete problems (like counting vertex covers or solutions to monotone 2-SAT) could be embedded within the geometry of $ C_{p^{n+2}} $. This leads me to propose a novel framework linking geometric complexity, game-theoretic verification, and structured function classes. Unlike existing approaches that treat computation and verification interchangeably, this work distinguishes them formally and shows how structural assumptions (like linearity of the threshold function) affect both feasibility and hardness. The idea integrates complexity theory, cooperative game theory, and geometric reasoning in a way not previously explored, offering both theoretical depth and implications for scalable explainability in AI systems.

