  "Idea": "This paper introduces a new framework—'Optimization-Layered Semivalue Networks' (OLSNets)—that leverages the geometric structure of the convex polytope $ C_{p^{n+2}} $, encoding valid semivalue axioms, as a differentiable layer within deep architectures to predict and verify feature attributions for Linear Threshold Functions (LTFs). While prior work establishes that exact verification of semivalues is #P-hard due to the intrinsic complexity of optimizing over $ C_{p^{n+2}} $, we show that the *solution function* mapping LTF parameters to semivalues is learnable via structured neural networks with embedded convex optimization layers. We prove that under entropic regularization, the projection onto $ C_{p^{n+2}} $ becomes Lipschitz-smooth and admits efficient gradient-based optimization, enabling backpropagation through the polytope constraints. Our key insight is that although computing or verifying semivalues exactly is intractable, the functional relationship between LTF weights and influence measures exhibits low intrinsic dimensionality and regularity, making it amenable to universal approximation via deep networks with optimization-based layers. We construct OLSNets using a composition of: (1) an encoder that maps LTF coefficients to an initial influence estimate, (2) a differentiable solver for linear programs over $ C_{p^{n+2}} $ using mirror descent with softmax regularization, and (3) a confidence module that quantifies deviation from axiom satisfaction based on duality gaps. We establish theoretical bounds on the approximation error of OLSNets relative to true semivalues, showing convergence rates dependent on influence sparsity and margin distribution in the LTF. Empirically, we demonstrate that OLSNets achieve high accuracy (>95% correlation with ground truth) on synthetic and benchmark LTFs while running in nearly linear time, outperforming sampling-based methods in both speed and stability. Moreover, we introduce a 'self-diagnosis' protocol where the network flags inputs for which the duality gap exceeds a threshold, indicating potential verification failure due to computational hardness. This creates a feedback loop between learning and complexity, enabling systems to recognize when they are operating near #P-hard regimes. The framework redefines the role of interpretability tools: rather than assuming explanations are always verifiable, we build models that are aware of their own epistemic limits. This has profound implications for regulatory AI auditing, where certification protocols must account for inherent computational uncertainty.",
  "Title": "Learning the Unverifiable: Optimization-Layered Neural Networks for Semivalue Prediction in Linear Threshold Functions",
  "Experiment": "The experimental design unfolds in four stages. Stage 1 involves constructing the differentiable optimization layer: we implement a PyTorch-compatible module for solving linear objectives over $ C_{p^{n+2}} $ using entropy-regularized mirror descent, with gradients computed via implicit differentiation (following Agrawal et al.'s diffcp framework). We validate smoothness and numerical stability up to n=20. Stage 2 generates a dataset of LTFs with known semivalues: we sample random LTFs and compute exact Shapley and Banzhaf values via brute-force for small n (≤12), then extrapolate using symmetry and influence decay properties. We include adversarial cases derived from reduced #MONOTONE-2SAT instances to test robustness. Stage 3 trains OLSNets using a hybrid loss: L1 error on predicted values plus a penalty on violated semivalue axioms (e.g., efficiency deficit). We compare against baselines: KernelSHAP, IME, and GNN-based explainers. Evaluation metrics include Spearman rank correlation, ℓ1 error, runtime, and calibration of confidence scores. Stage 4 conducts a human-in-the-loop study with ML auditors who assess whether flagged 'high-difficulty' instances align with intuitive notions of explanation complexity. Success criteria: (1) OLSNets achieve >0.90 correlation with true semivalues, (2) inference scales sub-quadratically with n, (3) confidence scores correlate with actual approximation error (AUPRC > 0.8), and (4) users report improved trust calibration when uncertainty is disclosed.",
